<article>
    <h1>NEW YEAR&#x2019;S EVE</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201213/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-13"><time>2020-12-13</time></a>
        - <span>FOOD &amp; DRINK</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>Restau­rants and ho­tels told The Sun­day Times they will shut by their usual clos­ing time – mostly by 10.30pm – to abide by Covid-19 re­stric­tions.</p>
    <p>Mediter­ranean restau­rant Riv­iera For­lino at One Fuller­ton, where din­ers usu­ally stay to ring in the New Year with fire­works at the Ma­rina Bay, has a plan in place if cur­rent re­stric­tions re­main.</p>
    <p>Din­ers who are part of its lux­u­ri­ous “La Belle Epoque”-themed New Year’s Eve eight-course din­ner (from $488++ a per­son) – which in­cludes free-flow cham­pagne – will re­ceive a spe­cial ham­per to count down at home.</p>
    <p>It will in­clude bread, cheese, pate en croute, house­made jams and pre­serves, as well as cham­pagne, says Mr Olivier Ben­del, chief ex­ec­u­tive of Deli­ciae Hospi­tal­ity Mar­ket­ing, which runs Riv­iera For­lino.</p>
    <p>He says: “Guests want to indulge dur­ing the hol­i­day sea­son and with 2020 be­ing a chal­leng­ing year for many, they are look­ing to treat them­selves this Christ­mas, to end the year on a more pos­i­tive, de­li­cious note.”</p>


